The cache is 2K bytes with 8-byte blocks, so it has 256 blocks. Each block holds two 4-byte elements. Array A starts at address 4096, and array B at 8192.  

During the loop, each iteration writes one element of A (4 bytes), so 256 writes occur. With a write-back policy, writes to memory happen only when a dirty block is evicted. Since the cache is direct-mapped and both arrays map to the same cache lines (addresses 4096 and 8192 are congruent modulo 2048), each access to B evicts the previously loaded A block, causing a write-back of the dirty A block. Over 256 iterations, every A block is written back exactly once, and each block is 8 bytes, so total bytes written to memory is \(256 \times 8 = 2048\).

